reviewText: This spin-off of Nickelodeon's ALL THAT, starring Keenan Thompson and Kel Mitchell, is a pretty funny movie. It can drag at times, but there are quite a few good bits, and the interaction between Keenan and Kel is great.  Plus, it co-stars both Abe Vigoda AND the fat guy from HEAD OF THE CLASS  (who also co-wrote)! What more could you possibly want in a movie?

Oh, Good Burger. A product of the 90's in every sense. It's got Kenan and Kel, it's got Less Than Jake, it's got Sinbad, it's got Carmen Electra in an auspicious near-debut, and it's got Abe Vigoda at the peak of his abilities. It's also a product of Nickelodeon in their peak years. Good Burger is stupidly funny, but it's not stupid to the point where the audience loses interest. It has a surprisingly compelling story and a lot of energy to carry it to it's wild finale. It's about as guilty as guilty pleasures get, but for anyone who enjoyed the film as a child and wants to revisit it, it holds up shockingly well. P.S. Imagine if Spike Lee had directed Good Burger. It probably would have been hailed as his best film since Do The Right Thing.

Good Burger is one of my favorite Nickelodeon films. This film is based on a clip from "All That". The film is about a high school boy named Dex (Thompson) who had no driver's license and wrecked his mom's car against his teacher's (Sinbad) car and he had to get a summer job to pay the damages or he will tell his mom about everything. A goofy fast food cashier named Ed (Mitchell) who sings "We are all Dudes"  helped Dex get a job at Good Burger and they compete against Mondo Burger owned by a greedy man (Schweiterman) who had a secret in his burgers. This film is so funny and I gave this film 5 stars.

Also in the mental hospital where they play that terrible music and George Clinton turns to Ed and says, "this music sucks".  LOL hilarious.

Let me just say that Good Burger is a movie of epic scale.  300...psh.  Watchmen...puh-lease.  If you don't agree that this movie is flawless on almost every level, you're in denial.  When Kenan and Kel meet Shaq to deliver his delicious Good Burgers, it's the most heart-warming moment in film history.  "SHAAAAAAAAQ!!!!"  The boys squeal.  Ah...it just tugs the heartstrings.

Honestly...the movie is awesome.  It harks back to a precious time in the mid-90's when movies on a truly epic scale didn't exist.  This was a diamond in the rough.

Being a person who loves both kid and family films, I purchased this movie from Suncoast Video in Livingston Mall.  After having left the mall, however, I did have my initial misgivings.  Would it live up to the "Good Burger" sketches that were regularly performed on Nickelodeon's tween version of "In Living Color"?

I'm happy--deliriously happy, I might add--to say that this movie did not disappoint.  I even showed it to my niece the next time she was over our house for a visit, and she and I laughed throughout the whole movie.  Kids' movies aren't like this anymore; if anything, the kids are smart-mouthed, irreverent, and disrespectful.  And they even managed to include a little moral:  that wealth and power aren't the things that will sustain.  Ultimately, doing a good job and selling a good product ("good burger") and keeping your customers happy will prove itself in the end.

Based on The Popular Skit on Nickelodeon's ''All That'', ''Good Burger'' Follows The Histarical Adventures of Friends Dexter and Ed, Who Work at The Famous Fast-Food Restruant, Good Burger. One Day, a Brand New Fast-Food Restruant, Mondo Burger, Opens Across The Street of Good Burger, in which is Trying To Put Good Burger Out of Buisness. Shortly After Figuring Out Mondo Burger Makes Thier Big Burger Meat Patties Out of Ileagal Supstences, Dexter and Ed Start Out on a Mission To Prove Mondo Burger Guilty as Charged. Though I Haven't Seen Much of the ''Good Burger'' Skit on Nickelodeon's Show ''All That'', But I Can Tell You, GOOD BURGER The Movie is One of The Best Kids Films Ever Made, and Not Only is it Funny For Kids, it's Funny For Teens and Adults if Thay Happen To Be Caught in The Right Mood To Watch Such A Film. Nickelodeon's Films That Are Based on Thier Shows/Skits, Thay Don't Live Up To What Thier Show/Skit Was, or Sometimes It's Just Not Good at All, But ''Good Burger'' Lives Up To Fans of The Skit. Kenan Thompson, Kel Mitchell and Everybody Who Were in This Film, Played Them Great and Histracally Funny. It's So Hard Finding a Good Kids Film That Doesn't Show any Thing So Violent, or Sexual (Even Though GOOD BURGER Gets it's PG Rating For Some Sex-Related Humor), or Language So Mild and Mean You Would Turn off Your TV or Walking Out of The Theater. GOOD BURGER is Nice, Good Fun For The Family. I Highly Recommend Everyone Watches GOOD BURGER. Also recommended For Fans of GOOD BURGER: SpongeBob SquarePants - The Complete 1st Season The SpongeBob SquarePants Movie Big Fat Liar The Amanda Show, Vol. 1 - Amanda, Please / The Amanda Show, Vol. 2 - The Girls' Room Animaniacs, Vol. 1-3 THERE ARE NO SPECIAL FEATURES ON THIS DVD But, Thay Could've Put at Least a trailer or a Making-of Feature. Overall Ratings Movie-5/5 DVD-1.5/5

There are fewer and fewer movies that can be watched by the entire family today.  It seems so many are filled with foul language, too much violence for the eyes to watch, or nudity that is usually uncalled for.  I hate to think what watching this R-rated junk does for our psyche.  On the other hand, we can watch the G-rated animations that seem to be the other end of the movie-watching spectrum.  Teenagers tend to think they are past watching these seemingly childish forms of entertainment, even though a lot of times the humor is directed at a more adult audience. Good Burger is funny, entertaining, and can be enjoyed by the entire family again and again!

Mondo Burger is opening right across the street from Good Burger. It literally puts Good Burger out of business. When Dexter tastes Ed's sauce for burgers, they open to the public, and they get the customers back. Soon, the manager at Mondo Burger named Kurt tries to steal Ed's recipe. Soon, they poison the sauce and send Ed and Dexter, and Otis to Demented Hills. They have until 10:00 in the morning to stop everyone from eating a Good Burger. When I took my kids to see this in the theater, it was pretty empty.  And I'm sure I was the only one really laughing throughout.  That's when I got that Good Burger was made more for people my age than theirs.  As they've gotten older, they've come to appreciate it more.

I know it was an expansion of an All That skit, but it had one big difference.  On All That, the Good Burger skit was mostly about Ed, played by Kel Mitchell, and his goofy talk and attitude.  This movie also had Kenan Thompson, as Dexter.  That made all the difference, because Dexter actually had a story.  Ed is funny, innocent, and what not, but he didn't bring the story by himself.

So, I'm watching this movie, wondering how Dexter's going to get out of his problem, when everyone somehow ends up in a mental institution.  And who's in the middle of the scene, but George Clinton, turning the dial on the radio to Knee Deep--one of my favorite songs of all time!  And when Kel leads the room in a rendition of the Thriller dance, I knew I'd found one of my new favorite movies.

Kenan and Kel, George Clinton, Sinbad as a tacky, over-the-top 70s jive talking teacher--this movie was hilarious!  And it's definitely one of the 7 happiest black movies of all time.

The review at the top will tell you this is a kids movie.  Nope!  Adults can enjoy it too.  It's a really funny movie.  It's about two burger restaurants that compete with each other.  Both restaurants are right across the street from each other.  As you can probably guess, one restaurant has a bunch of jerks working there, determined to close down the restaurant across the street.  Meanwhile, the other burger place has well-meaning, though not necessarily the most intelligent bunch of employees working there (these are the GOOD guys).  Kick back and enjoy.

Who would have thought Kel Mitchell and Kenan Thompson could pull it off? Just thinking about it sends up a lot of red flags doesn't it? Sure, there slapstick style comedy works well on Nickelodeon but that's television.  A half hour of funny on the T.V. screen can turn into 95 minutes of pure stupidity and torture when stretched into a full length motion picture if it's not done correctly.

Believe it or not, `Good Burger' was done absolutely to perfection (pun intended). Kenan and Kel star as Dexter and Ed, two high school kids working at the local fast-food restaurant known as, Good Burger. Yes, the movie contains loads of the over-the-top physical comedy the two are known for, but it also boasts a very inventive, well thought out script containing lots of quotable lines, a strong storyline and a great supporting cast that keeps your interest peaked from beginning to end.

Your children will love it and so will you!

Yes, the film does have the "slime factor" so prevalent in Nickelodeon's productions.
Yes, the film has jokes that only a seven-year-old could love.
Yes, the film features Sinbad and Abe Vigoda in supporting roles as "adults" that are the brunt of youngsters antics.
Yes, the film has a likeable character with the intelligence of a cucumber and a genuine innocence that endears him to all.

But, it is a delightful little movie that appeals to a cross-section of the audience in a time when there are few genuine non-offensive family films.
And, it does have one really cool dance number to "Knee Deep" featuring the funk man himself, George Clinton.

The title doesn't do justice worsham to this film.
Even though I'm not the target demographic for this terrific kids' movie, I couldn't keep from getting in on the excitement. It felt like I whooped and hollered at the screen every five minutes!
Props to Brian Robbins for directing such a joy. It's obvious the skill and enthusiasm displayed in this film carry over into his producing duties on the hit WB show "Smallville."
The best part: Robbins' choice to enlist Stewart Copeland to contribute music. Copeland wrote many of the best songs performed by the Police, and his contribution to this film (and the wicked "Gridlock'd") is immeasurable.
My only complaint is that they should have called this movie "Awesome Burger!"

The debate which once raged about the relative merits of Citizen Kane vs. Casablanca can now fall silent: As the end of the twentieth century nears, Good Burger has achieved cinematic perfection.
The story of Ed (Kel Mitchell) and Dexter (Kenan Thompson) and how they rescue the Good Burger restaurant from destruction at the hands of the domineering Mondo Burger is more than just the story of warriors battling the onslaught of corporate tyranny; it is a metaphor for the transcendence of the human spirit. Like our Homeric heroes Ed and Dexter, each of us must struggle to find a place in the universe -- only then can we truly be free.
Not since Henry Fonda won for "On Golden Pond," has an actor nearing death deserved a nomination more than Abe Vigoda. His portrait of proud Otis, the aging fast food employee, is both complex and compelling -- and a powerful comment on the plight of geriatrics everywhere.
Director Brian Robbins's masterful skills in telling this epic of survival and hope reduced the audience to stunned silence; many, including this reviewer, wept openly.

The sleeper hit of the year!!  I wasn't planning on watching this one, but since I worked in a video store when it came out, I involuntarily saw it.  I was amazed that a kid's channel could come up with an entertaining, yet very informative treatise on the evils of the corporate structure.  And how anyone can beat "The MAN", even a couple of regular(?) guys like Ed and Dexter.  Working in a independent video store at the time, I too faced a similar struggle vs "The MAN", in this case Blockbu---r Video, who had recently moved in next store.  Unlike Ed and Dexter at the Goodburger however, my store lost.....  But nonetheless, I was still able to appreciate the delightful story and funny antics of two average guys vs the Corporate Overlords across the street.

I am outraged that this movie was passed up for an Academy Award.  Instead movies like Titanic, and Braveheart are snatching the Oscars like butter, and movies like Good Burger and The Power Rangers are left in the dust.  Not since Lucielle Ball have I seen comedy like these two young actors,  Kenan and Kel.  They're the Abbott and Costello of the 90's.  When I saw  this movie, I laughed and cried.  The emotional roller coaster Good Burger  takes you on is rivaled only by The Green Mile.  I can't say enough good  things about this masterpiece on film.  If you could frame a movie and put  it next to the Mona Lisa this would be the one.  Don't let this gem of a  film escape your clutches.  BUY IT NOW!
